d with grand metaphysical ideas-actually had a specific conception of civil society and the state. In Hegel's view, public institutions represent the fulfillment of deep subjective needs-and in that sense, demonstrate that the real is the rational, because what surrounds us is the product of our collective mindedness. This groundbreaking analysis will guide the study of Hegel and nineteenth-century political thought for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aObjectivity. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSubjectivity. 4aHegel. 4agerman classical philosophy. 4ainstitutionalism. 4aphilosophy of law. 4apolitical philosophy. 4arights. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aGinsburg, Daniela.1 aShuster, Martin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226023946423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226023946.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles